2.  National  (individual;  climate  change  technology  policy  experts,  project 
coordinator, 90–110 person-months) 

4.  The experts will 
(i)  coordinate subproject activities; 
(ii)  support  international  experts  in  screening  and  identifying  suitable  DMCs  for 
assistance; 
(iii)  provide initial review of national policy strategies, including technology policies 
and climate change policies; 
(iv)  take  the  lead  in  organizing  consultation  meetings  with  key  stakeholders  in 
regional departments; 
(v)  take part in consultation meetings on planning and policy with national and/or 
subnational government and other key stakeholders; 
(vi)  provide support for the assessment of current national and/or subnational policy 
frameworks  and  review  government  plans  and  commitments  on  promoting 
climate technologies and on standards, and regulations for climate technology 
transfer and deployment; 
(vii)  support the international experts in providing inputs to the countries’ development 
strategies and investment plans; 
(viii)  support  the  international  experts  in  assisting  the  development  of  plans  and 
policies to promote climate technologies; 
(ix)  conduct training and dissemination activities with DMC government agencies; 
(x)  support the head of the pilot technology center in general management activities, 
as required; 
(xi)  provide inputs to progress reports and briefing notes; 
(xii)  provide administrative and technical support, as required; 
(xiii)  organize workshops and meetings with DMC stakeholders; and 
(xiv)  create and manage TA database and records. 

B.  Subproject  B:  Promotion  of  Direct  Investment  in  Priority  Climate  Technology 
Projects 

1.  International  (individual;  climate  change  technology  experts,  70–90  person-
months) 

5.  The experts will 
(i)  develop and monitor subproject work plans and budgets; 
(ii)  supervise the team to ensure all deliverables are submitted on schedule; 
(iii)  refine prioritization criteria for selecting projects, as necessary; 
(iv)  screen and identify possible candidate projects from ADB project pipeline for 
assistance; 
(v)  develop, in close consultation with regional departments, a long list of candidate 
projects to assist; 
(vi)  establish assistance needs for projects and develop a short list of projects to 
assist; 
(vii)  provide inputs to prefeasibility and feasibility studies, as required, for identified 
projects; 
(viii)  provide  inputs  to  alternative  technology  analysis  and  technical  design,  as 
required, for identified projects. 
(ix)  provide inputs to resource potential assessments for identified mitigation projects, 
as required;

14  Appendix 3 
(x)  provide inputs to technology resilience assessments, as required, for identified  
adaptation projects; 
(xi)  provide capacity building for DMC stakeholders in identified investment projects, 
as required; 
(xii)  report to the head of the technology center on subproject management; and 
(xiii)  prepare progress reports, briefing notes, correspondence, and other technical 
documents, as required. 

2.  National (individual; climate change technology experts, project assistant; 40–60 
person-months) 

6.  The experts will 
(i)  assist in identifying additional investment projects for potential ADB assistance; 
(ii)  assist in identifying and assessing candidate projects for assistance from ADB 
project pipeline; 
(iii)  assist  in  providing  technology-related  inputs  to  pre-feasibility  and  feasibility 
studies, resource potential assessments, and technology resilience assessments 
for identified projects, as required; 
(iv)  coordinate subproject activities; 
(v)  provide administrative and technical support; and 
(vi)  assist with documentation and reporting. 

C.  Subproject C: Promotion of Investment in Climate Technology Products through 
Venture Capital Funds 

1.  International  (firms  and  individual;  energy  efficiency  technology  experts, 
renewable  energy  technology  experts,  water  technology  experts,  and  other 
climate technology experts, as required; 350–370 person-months) 

7.  The experts will 
(i)  manage and coordinate provision of services to selected fund managers; 
(ii)  assist  in  engaging  additional  firm  or  individual  experts  to  provide  identified 
supplementary  technology-related  advisory  services,  including  preparation  of 
terms of reference and ranking and selection of candidates; 
(iii)  conduct  reviews  of  emerging  climate  change  mitigation  and  adaptation 
technologies across sectors; 
(iv)  identify candidate start-up firms; 
(v)  screen and assess proposals received from fund managers; 
(vi)  assist in monitoring progress of investments by fund managers, with respect to 
technology aspects; 
(vii)  provide technical support to potential climate technology venture capital funds in 
more challenging yet promising countries, sectors, frontier markets, or regions, 
such as Southeast Asia; 
(viii)  prepare progress reports, briefing notes, correspondence, and other technical 
documents on the TA; and 
(ix)  conduct workshops to disseminate findings.

